\ examples/107-open-ended-rewrite.6th
\ Track 2.3 — open-ended hypergraph rewriting, no halting predicate.
\
\ Question: when a minimal Wolfram-style substrate rewrite rule is
\ run for a FIXED number of iterations (no target-min, no halting
\ predicate), what topology emerges?  This directly addresses the
\ "Pilot D cosmogenesis is hand-coded because the halting predicate
\ encodes the desired output" critique.
\
\ Pilot D (demo 42) uses NSUM(O) >= target-min as halting predicate.
\ Author tunes target-min so that halt occurs at the desired 13-node
\ graph.  This demo removes the halting predicate entirely — the rule
\ runs for an iteration count chosen WITHOUT consulting the substrate
\ state.  Outcome topology is then a pure function of (rule, initial,
\ iteration-count), no author intervention.
\
\ Wolfram-style rewrite:
\
\   For each existing edge (a, b):
\     MARK c (fresh node)
\     EDGE+ (a, c)
\     EDGE+ (b, c)
\
\ Initial: single edge 1 → 2 (after MARKing both nodes).
\
\ Predicted growth (substrate-derived):
\   Iteration k:
\     edges_before = E_k
\     each edge adds 2 new edges → E_{k+1} = E_k + 2 * E_k = 3 * E_k
\     nodes_before = N_k
\     each edge adds 1 new node → N_{k+1} = N_k + E_k
\
\   Recurrences:
\     E_0 = 1, E_1 = 3, E_2 = 9, E_3 = 27, E_4 = 81  (3^k growth)
\     N_0 = 2, N_1 = 3, N_2 = 6, N_3 = 15, N_4 = 42, N_5 = 123
\
\ The 3^k edge growth is exponential — substrate-derived from a
\ minimal rule.  This is genuinely an emergent property (rule does
\ not encode "produce 3-fold edge growth"; the rule encodes "add
\ Wolfram-step output"; 3^k falls out of the recurrence).
\
\ Topological invariants to measure:
\   - E / N ratio (asymptotically 3^k / k 3^k ≈ 1/k → 0, sparse)
\   - Max out-degree per node
\   - Number of distinct out-degrees (degree-distribution width)
\   - Average path length (approximated by diameter via NSUM probe)

use prelude
use graph
use debug

\ ============================================================
\ Setup: initial edge 1 → 2.
\ ============================================================

MARK "n1" store
MARK "n2" store
"n1" load "n2" load EDGE+

NODES 2 assert-eq
EDGES 1 assert-eq

\ ============================================================
\ Rule: for each edge (a, b), spawn fresh c and add edges (a,c), (b,c).
\
\ Implementation: EACH-EDGE iterates a SNAPSHOT of edges, so new
\ edges added by the rule body are NOT re-visited within the same
\ EACH-EDGE call.  This is exactly the Wolfram-style "step" semantics.
\ ============================================================

: wolfram-step ( a b -- )
  "we-b" store   "we-a" store
  MARK "we-c" store
  "we-a" load "we-c" load EDGE+
  "we-b" load "we-c" load EDGE+ ;

\ ============================================================
\ Iteration 1: 1 edge → 3 edges, 2 nodes → 3 nodes
\
\ Before: {(1,2)}, nodes {1,2}
\ After:  {(1,2), (1,3), (2,3)}, nodes {1,2,3}
\ ============================================================

' wolfram-step EACH-EDGE
NODES 3 assert-eq
EDGES 3 assert-eq

\ ============================================================
\ Iteration 2: 3 edges → 9 edges, 3 nodes → 6 nodes
\
\ Each of the 3 edges spawns 1 new node + 2 new edges.
\ ============================================================

' wolfram-step EACH-EDGE
NODES 6 assert-eq
EDGES 9 assert-eq

\ ============================================================
\ Iteration 3: 9 → 27 edges, 6 → 15 nodes
\ ============================================================

' wolfram-step EACH-EDGE
NODES 15 assert-eq
EDGES 27 assert-eq

\ ============================================================
\ Iteration 4: 27 → 81 edges, 15 → 42 nodes
\ ============================================================

' wolfram-step EACH-EDGE
NODES 42 assert-eq
EDGES 81 assert-eq

\ ============================================================
\ Substrate-derived growth law VERIFIED: edges_k = 3^k, nodes follow
\ Σ 3^i recurrence.  These numbers (42, 81 at k=4) were NOT chosen
\ by the author; they are the unique fixed-point of the Wolfram-step
\ rule applied to the initial single-edge substrate.
\
\ Compare to Pilot D (13 nodes, 49 edges):
\   Pilot D applies a tuned rule with halting predicate calibrated
\   to produce exactly 13 nodes.  Author chose target-min so halt
\   fires at 13.
\
\   This demo applies a generic Wolfram-step with NO halting
\   predicate.  Output topology (42 nodes, 81 edges at k=4) is
\   determined purely by (rule, initial-edge, k=4).  Author cannot
\   tune the topology without changing the rule or k — and the rule
\   itself encodes NO target.
\
\ This is an HONEST EMERGENT topology in the substrate-monism sense:
\ the substrate state after k=4 is determined by the substrate
\ semantics, not by author intention.
\ ============================================================

\ ============================================================
\ Topological probe: out-degree distribution at k=4.
\
\ For Wolfram-step output:
\   - The original two nodes (1, 2) accumulate out-edges with every
\     iteration as new c's get edges from them
\   - Newly-spawned nodes have out-degree 0 (only incoming edges
\     from their "parent" pair)
\
\ Verify: node 1 has out-degree = number of new c's it gained edges
\ to over k=4 iterations.
\ ============================================================

\ Count nodes by out-degree.
0 "deg0" store
0 "deg-ge1" store
0 "deg-ge5" store
0 "deg-ge10" store

: count-by-degree ( n -- )
  dup OUT 0 = if "deg0" load 1 + "deg0" store else
    dup OUT 1 >= if "deg-ge1" load 1 + "deg-ge1" store then
    dup OUT 5 >= if "deg-ge5" load 1 + "deg-ge5" store then
    dup OUT 10 >= if "deg-ge10" load 1 + "deg-ge10" store then
  then drop ;

' count-by-degree EACH

\ Most nodes (the spawned c's of later iterations) have OUT=0.
\ A small number of "old" nodes have growing out-degrees.
\
\ This distribution is SUBSTRATE-DERIVED, not authored.  Author
\ does not know in advance how the (3^k / N_k) ratio will distribute
\ across degree-classes.

\ ============================================================
\ Sensitivity probe: tiny change to initial substrate → divergent
\ topology?
\ ============================================================

RESET
MARK "m1" store
MARK "m2" store
MARK "m3" store
"m1" load "m2" load EDGE+
"m2" load "m3" load EDGE+    \ 2 initial edges instead of 1

' wolfram-step EACH-EDGE
EDGES 6 assert-eq           \ 2 edges → 6 (each spawns 2 new)
NODES 5 assert-eq           \ 3 → 5 (2 new c nodes)

' wolfram-step EACH-EDGE
EDGES 18 assert-eq
NODES 11 assert-eq

' wolfram-step EACH-EDGE
EDGES 54 assert-eq
NODES 29 assert-eq

\ Starting with 2 edges instead of 1 gives factor-2 scaling at every
\ iteration: edges_k(initial=2) = 2 · 3^k vs edges_k(initial=1) = 3^k.
\ The exponential growth rate is INVARIANT in the rule, but the
\ multiplier depends on initial conditions.
\
\ Universal property: edge growth ratio = 3 per iteration, independent
\ of initial substrate.  This is substrate-derived (rule encodes 3-
\ output expansion per edge), invariant under initial-conditions
\ perturbation.

\ Growth ratio check.
54 18 / 3 assert-eq         \ ratio between iterations = 3
18 6  / 3 assert-eq

cr
